= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|{{vbw|POL}}||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||8th||6th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''2'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|{{vbw|RUS}}||colspan=6|Part of ''{{vbw|URS}}''||\u2022||bgcolor=silver|2nd||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||bgcolor=#9acdff|4th||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||'''3'''\n|- bgcolor= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|{{vbw|SRB}}||colspan=6|Part of ''{{vbw|YUG}}''||colspan=3|Part of ''{{vbw|SCG}}''||5th||7th||bgcolor=silver|2nd||9th||'''4'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|{{vbw|KOR}}||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||5th||7th||7th||6th||5th||bgcolor=#9acdff|4th||9th||8th||9th||6th||6th||'''13'''\n|- bgcolor= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|{{vbw|ESP}}||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||11th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''1'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|{{vbw|THA}}||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||10th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''1'''\n|- bgcolor= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|{{vbw|TUN}}||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||8th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||12th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''2'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|{{vbw|TUR}}||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||7th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''1'''\n|- bgcolor= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|{{vbw|USA}}||6th||7th||bgcolor=#9acdff|4th||\u2022||\u2022||bgcolor=#9acdff|4th||7th||9th||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=silver|2nd||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=silver|2nd||'''11'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|{{vbw|URU}}||style=\"border:3px solid red\"|10th||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||'''1'''\n|-\n|align=\"center\" colspan=15|'''Discontinued nations'''\n|- bgcolor= #E8E8F0\n|align=left|''{{vbw|GDR}}''||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||\u2022||6th||colspan=8|See {{vbw|GER}}||'''1'''\n|- bgcolor= #FFFFFF\n|align=left|''{{vbw|URS}}''||bgcolor=gold|1st||8th||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||bgcolor=silver|2nd||bgcolor=#CC9966|3rd||colspan=7|See {{vbw|RUS}} etc.||'''6'''\n|}\n\n==[[Most valuable player|MVP]] by edition==\n*[[1973 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1973]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Jo Hea-jung]]|KOR}}<ref>{{cite web |title=\ubc30\uad6c \uc870\ud61c\uc815 |trans-title=Volleyball Jo Hea-jung |url=https://news.joins.com/article/1365179 |language=Korean |date=20 Dec 1973 |accessdate=2 Mar 2020}}</ref>\n*[[1981 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1981]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|Sun Jinfang|CHN}}\n*[[1985 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1985]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Lang Ping]]|CHN}}\n*[[1989 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1989]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Mireya Luis]]|CUB}}\n*[[1991 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1991]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Caren Kemner]]|USA}}\n*[[1995 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1995]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Mireya Luis]]|CUB}}\n*[[1999 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1999]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Taismary Ag\u00fcero]]|CUB}}\n*[[2003 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2003]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Ma\u0142gorzata Glinka-Mogentale|Ma\u0142gorzata Glinka]]|POL}}\n*[[2007 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2007]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Simona Gioli]]|ITA}}\n*[[2011 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2011]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Carolina Costagrande]]|ITA}}\n*[[2015 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2015]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Zhu Ting (volleyball)|Zhu Ting]]|CHN}}\n*[[2019 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2019]] \u2013 {{flagathlete|[[Zhu Ting (volleyball)|Zhu Ting]]|CHN}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Volleyball|Sports|Japan}}\n*[[Volleyball at the Summer Olympics]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Champions Cup]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Prix]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League]]\n*[[List of Indoor Volleyball World Medalists]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fivb.com/ FIVB]\n\n{{FIVB Volleyball World Cup}}\n{{Volleyball}}\n{{International volleyball (Women)}}\n{{Women's Volleyball World Cup winners}}\n{{Main world cups}}\n\n[[Category:FIVB Volleyball World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1973]]\n[[Category:International volleyball competitions]]\n[[Category:International women's volleyball competitions]]\n[[Category:Quadrennial sporting events]]\n[[Category:World cups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports league\n| current_season = 2019 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2019\n| logo           =\n| pixels         = \n| caption        = \n| sport          = Volleyball\n| founded        = 1973\n| inaugural      = [[1973 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1973]]\n| ceo            = {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Ary Gra\u00e7a]]\n| fame           = \n| motto          = \n| teams          = 12\n| continent      = International ([[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|FIVB]])\n| champion       = {{vbw|CHN}} (5th title) \n| most_champs    = {{vbw|CHN}} (5 titles)\n| singles        = \n| TV             = \n| website        = [http://worldcup.2019.fivb.com/en FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup]\n}}\n\nThe '''FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup''' is an international [[volleyball]] competition contested by the senior women's national teams of the members of ''{{lang|fr|F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball}}'' ([[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|FIVB]]), the sport's global governing body. Initially the tournament was played in the year following the Olympic Games, but since [[1991 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|1991]] the World Cup has been awarded in the year preceding the Olympic Games. The current champion is [[China women's national volleyball team|China]], which won its fifth title at the [[2019 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|2019 tournament]].\n\nThe current format of the competition involves 12 teams, including the automatically qualifying host nation [[Japan women's national volleyball team|Japan]], competing in the tournament phase for the title at venues within the host nation over a period of about two weeks. The World Cup (with exception of the 2019 edition) acts as the first qualification event for the following year's [[Volleyball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] with the top two teams qualifying.\n\nThe 13 World Cup tournaments have been won by five different national teams. [[China women's national volleyball team|China]]<!--For consistency, British English is used throughout the article, which treats teams as plural nouns, e.g., \"China are\" instead of \"China is\".--> have won five times. The other World Cup winners are [[Cuba women's national volleyball team|Cuba]], with four titles; [[Italy women's national volleyball team|Italy]], with two titles; and [[Japan women's national volleyball team|Japan]] and [[Russia women's national volleyball team|Russia]] (as [[Soviet Union women's national volleyball team|Soviet Union]]), with one title each.\n\nThis tournament should not be confused with the [[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nThe World Cup was created in 1965 with the purpose of partially filling the gap between the two most important volleyball tournaments, the [[Volleyball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] and the [[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship|World Championship]], which take place in alternating 4-year cycles. The establishment of a third international competition would leave only one in every four years with no major events. The World Cup has a smaller entry than the World Championship, with at most 12 teams.\n\nThe World Cup was to be held in the year following the Olympic Games. The first two tournaments were for men's volleyball only; in 1973, a women's tournament was also introduced. Originally, each tournament had a different host, but in 1977 the competition was transferred to [[Japan]] on a permanent basis.\n\nIn the 1990s, the installment of annual international events such as the [[FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]] and the [[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Prix|Grand Prix]] made the original motivations for the creation of the World Cup obsolete. Instead of letting a consolidated event disappear for lack of interest, the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|FIVB]] decided to change its format in 1991: it would be held in the year preceding, and not following, the Olympic Games; and it would be considered a first international Olympic qualification tournament, granting the winner a direct berth in the games.\n\nThis move saved the competition. The possibility of securing an early berth for the Olympic Games, thus avoiding extraneous and in some cases tight continental qualification procedures, became a consistent motivation for the national federations to participate in the World Cup. In 1995, the number of Olympic spots granted at the competition was increased to three, as it remained until 2011. In 2015 the number of spots was only two again.\n\n===Winners===\nThe Women's World Cup has had not one great winner, like its counterpart for men's volleyball, but two: [[China women's national volleyball team|China]] and [[Cuba women's national volleyball team|Cuba]].\n\nThe first edition of the tournament was won by the [[Soviet Union women's national volleyball team|Soviet Union]]. [[Japan women's national volleyball team|Japan]], the runner-up of 1973, took the gold in 1977. With the help of superstar player [[Lang Ping]], China won the following two editions, in 1981 and 1985.\n\nThen Cuba stepped forward to begin its amazing World Cup career, winning its first title in 1989. With the tournament now as an Olympic qualifier, there followed three more consecutive victories, in 1991, 1995 and 1999.\n\nChina came back in 2003 with a remarkably offensive team to win its third title.\n\n[[Italy women's national volleyball team|Italy]] won the 2007 edition with an outstanding record of eleven wins in eleven games and only two sets left to the opponents (both lost against [[Serbia women's national volleyball team|Serbia]]). Italy took a second win in a row in 2011, getting the better hand on United States and China. In 2015, China regained the title.\n\n==Competition formula==\nThe World Cup is the most stable from all competition formulas employed by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Volleyball|FIVB]]. The following rules apply:\n\n*The competition takes place in Japan.\n*Twelve teams participate in each event: ten qualified, two per invitation.\n**[[Japan women's national volleyball team|Japan]] are always pre-qualified as host nation.\n**The winners of the [[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]] in the previous year are automatically granted a spot.\n**The champion and runner-up of each continental tournament of that year are granted two spots.\n**Since the 1999 edition, only teams not yet qualified for the following Olympic Games can compete in the World Cup; hence hosts of the following year's Olympic Games are not allowed to compete. There will be an exception for the 2019 World Cup, as the tournament will be hosted by Japan and the country will host the [[2020 Summer Olympics]].\n*The competition is divided in exactly two phases (called \"legs\").\n**Teams are divided in two pools.\n***At the first leg, each team plays one match against all other teams in its pool.\n**At the second leg, each team plays one match against all the teams in the other pool.\n**Matches take place continuously through two weeks, with one-day breaks every two or three days. Each day, six matches are played.\n**Final standings are calculated by usual volleyball criteria: match points, numbers of matches won, sets ratio (the total number of sets won divided by the total number of sets lost), points ratio, direct confrontation.\n*The top two teams in overall standings, regardless of pools, qualify for the following [[Olympic Games]].\n*The tournament implements very tight line-up restrictions: only twelve players are allowed, and no replacement is permitted, even in the case of injuries.\n\n==Results summary==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; width: 100%; text-align: center;\"\n|- bgcolor=#c1d8ff\n!rowspan=2 width=6%|Year\n!rowspan=2 width=12%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=15 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!colspan=3|Final\n!width=1% rowspan=15 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!colspan=3|3rd place match\n!width=1% rowspan=15 bgcolor=#ffffff|\n!rowspan=2 width=5%|Teams\n|- bgcolor=#efefef\n!width=14%|Champions\n!width=9%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=14%|3rd place\n!width=9%|Score\n!width=14%|4th place\n|-\n|1973<br />[[1973 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|URU}}<br>[[Uruguay]]\n|'''{{vbw-big|URS|1955}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|JPN|1947}}\n|{{vbw-big|KOR|1949}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|PER}}\n|10\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1977<br />[[1977 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN|1947}}<br>[[Japan]]\n|'''{{vbw-big|JPN|1947}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|CUB}}\n|{{vbw-big|KOR|1949}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|CHN}}\n|8\n|-\n|1981<br />[[1981 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN|1947}}<br>[[Japan]]\n|'''{{vbw-big|CHN}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|JPN|1947}}\n|{{vbw-big|URS}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|USA}}\n|8\n|- bgcolor=#E8E8F0\n|1985<br />[[1985 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN|1947}}<br>[[Japan]]\n|'''{{vbw-big|CHN}}'''\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|CUB}}\n|{{vbw-big|URS}}\n|[[Round-robin tournament|Round-robin]]\n|{{vbw-big|JPN|1947}}\n|8\n|-\n|1989<br />[[1989 FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup|Details]]\n|{{flagicon|JPN|1947}}<br>[[Japan]]\n|'''{{vbw-big|CUB}}'''\n