 the Summer Olympics]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Men's World Cup]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Women's World Championship]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Champions Cup]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball World Grand Prix]]\n*[[FIVB Volleyball Women's Nations League]]\n*[[List of Indoor Volleyball World Medalists]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fivb.com/ FIVB]\n\n{{FIVB Volleyball World Cup}}\n{{Volleyball}}\n{{International volleyball (Women)}}\n{{Women's Volleyball World Cup winners}}\n{{Main world cups}}\n\n[[Category:FIVB Volleyball World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:FIVB Volleyball Women's World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1973]]\n[[Category:International volleyball competitions]]\n[[Category:International women's volleyball competitions]]\n[[Category:Quadrennial sporting events]]\n[[Category:World cups]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FIVB_Volleyball_Women%27s_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Correos (Barcelona Metro)", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name            = Correos\n| type            = [[Barcelona Metro]] [[rapid transit]] station\n| style           = \n| image           = Estaci\u00f3 de Correus.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_caption   = \n| address         = [[Via Laietana, Barcelona|Via Laietana]], [[Ciutat Vella]], [[Barcelona]]\n| country         = \n| coordinates     = {{coord|41|22|55|N|2|10|53|E|source:kolossus-cawiki|display=inline,title}}\n| line            = \n| other           = \n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| depth           = \n| levels          = \n| tracks          = 1\n| parking         = \n| bicycle         = \n| baggage_check   = \n| opened          = 1934\n| closed          = 1972\n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Transports Metropolitans de Barcelona]]\n| zone            = \n| smartcardname   = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = None (abandoned)\n| map_type        = Spain Barcelona#Spain\n| map_caption     = Location in Barcelona##Location in Spain\n}}\n'''Correos''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]) or '''Correus''' ([[Catalan language|Catalan]]) was a former [[Barcelona metro]] station. The station site is located on what is now line [[Barcelona metro line 4|L4]] between the existing stations of [[Jaume I (Barcelona Metro)|Jaume I]] and [[Barceloneta (Barcelona Metro)|Barceloneta]], and under the street of [[Via Laietana, Barcelona|Via Laietana]].<ref name=lfdndm>{{cite web| url = http://www.directe.cat/noticia/9550/lestacio-fantasma-del-metro-de-barcelona-mes-ben-conservada-es-la-de-gaudi-lunica-que-no-h-9550 | title =L'estaci\u00f3 'fantasma' del metro de Barcelona m\u00e9s ben conservada \u00e9s la de Gaud\u00ed, l'\u00fanica que no ha funcionat mai | language = Catalan | publisher = Directe!Cat | accessdate = 2014-12-05}}</ref><ref name=tmap>{{cite web | url = http://cartometro.com/cartes/metro-tram-barcelona/ | title = Track map of the Barcelona Metro | publisher = cartometro.com | accessdate = 2014-12-02}}</ref>\n\nThe station opened in 1934 as a terminus of a branch of the [[Gran Metro de Barcelona]], Barcelona's first metro line. The Gran Metro de Barcelona came to be known as  line [[Barcelona metro line 3|L3]] but Correos remained the terminus of a branch. The station was dismantled in 1972 to permit the extension of the line into [[La Barceloneta]], as part of the integration of the branch into line L4.<ref name=lfdndm/><ref name=tmap/>\n\nAlong with [[Banc (Barcelona Metro) |Banco]], it is one of the two metro stations on Via Laietana that have disappeared.<ref name=lfdndm/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Disused Barcelona Metro stations]]\n*[[Gaud\u00ed (Barcelona Metro)]]\n*[[Banc (Barcelona Metro)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070404122532/http://perso.wanadoo.es/assotram/bcnmetrolost.htm Lost Barcelona metro stations (with photos)]\n\n{{Barcelona Metro line 3}}\n\n[[Category:Disused Barcelona Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Abandoned rapid transit stations]]\n[[Category:Defunct railway stations in Spain]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1934]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1972]]\n\n{{Catalonia-railstation-stub}}\n{{Barcelona-metro-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name            = Correos\n| type            = [[Barcelona Metro]] [[rapid transit]] station\n| style           = \n| image           = Estaci\u00f3 de Correus.jpg\n| image_size      = \n| image_caption   = \n| address         = [[Via Laietana, Barcelona|Via Laietana]], [[Ciutat Vella]], [[Barcelona]]\n| country         = \n| coordinates     = {{coord|41|22|55|N|2|10|53|E|source:kolossus-cawiki|display=inline,title}}\n| line            = \n| other           = \n| structure       = Underground\n| platform        = 2 [[side platform]]s\n| depth           = \n| levels          = \n| tracks          = 1\n| parking         = \n| bicycle         = \n| baggage_check   = \n| opened          = 1934\n| closed          = 1972\n| rebuilt         = \n| electrified     = \n| ADA             = \n| code            = \n| owned           = [[Transports Metropolitans de Barcelona]]\n| zone            = \n| smartcardname   = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former          = \n| passengers      = \n| pass_year       = \n| pass_percent    = \n| pass_system     = \n| mpassengers     = \n| services        = None (abandoned)\n| map_type        = Spain Barcelona#Spain\n| map_caption     = Location in Barcelona##Location in Spain\n}}\n'''Correos''' ([[Spanish language|Spanish]]) or '''Correus''' ([[Catalan language|Catalan]]) was a former [[Barcelona metro]] station. The station site is located on what is now line [[Barcelona metro line 4|L4]] between the existing stations of [[Jaume I (Barcelona Metro)|Jaume I]] and [[Barceloneta (Barcelona Metro)|Barceloneta]], and under the street of [[Via Laietana, Barcelona|Via Laietana]].<ref name=lfdndm>{{cite web| url = http://www.directe.cat/noticia/9550/lestacio-fantasma-del-metro-de-barcelona-mes-ben-conservada-es-la-de-gaudi-lunica-que-no-h-9550 | title =L'estaci\u00f3 'fantasma' del metro de Barcelona m\u00e9s ben conservada \u00e9s la de Gaud\u00ed, l'\u00fanica que no ha funcionat mai | language = Catalan | publisher = Directe!Cat | accessdate = 2014-12-05}}</ref><ref name=tmap>{{cite web | url = http://carto.metro.free.fr/cartes/metro-tram-barcelona/ | title = Track map of the Barcelona Metro | publisher = carto.metro.free.fr | accessdate = 2014-12-02}}</ref>\n\nThe station opened in 1934 as a terminus of a branch of the [[Gran Metro de Barcelona]], Barcelona's first metro line. The Gran Metro de Barcelona came to be known as  line [[Barcelona metro line 3|L3]] but Correos remained the terminus of a branch. The station was dismantled in 1972 to permit the extension of the line into [[La Barceloneta]], as part of the integration of the branch into line L4.<ref name=lfdndm/><ref name=tmap/>\n\nAlong with [[Banc (Barcelona Metro) |Banco]], it is one of the two metro stations on Via Laietana that have disappeared.<ref name=lfdndm/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Disused Barcelona Metro stations]]\n*[[Gaud\u00ed (Barcelona Metro)]]\n*[[Banc (Barcelona Metro)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070404122532/http://perso.wanadoo.es/assotram/bcnmetrolost.htm Lost Barcelona metro stations (with photos)]\n\n{{Barcelona Metro line 3}}\n\n[[Category:Disused Barcelona Metro stations]]\n[[Category:Abandoned rapid transit stations]]\n[[Category:Defunct railway stations in Spain]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1934]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1972]]\n\n{{Catalonia-railstation-stub}}\n{{Barcelona-metro-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Carto.metro", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update link to cartometro.com (301:permanent move)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correos_(Barcelona_Metro)"}
{"title_page": "The Crusader (1932 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1932 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Crusader\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Frank R. Strayer]]\n| producer       = [[Phil Goldstone]] <br> [[Larry Darmour]]\n| writer         = [[Wilson Collison]] (play)<br>[[Edward T. Lowe Jr.]] (sceenplay)\n| starring       = [[Evelyn Brent]]\n| editing        = Otis Garrett\n| distributor    = [[Majestic Pictures]]<br>Capitol Film Exchange (State's Rights)\n| released       = {{film date|1932|10|5}}\n| runtime        = 65 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Crusader''''' is a 1932 American [[Pre-Code Hollywood|pre-Code]]<!--The \"p\" in pre-Code should be lowercased within narrative. See usage in captions and narrative at Pre-Code Hollywood page--> [[drama film]] based upon the play of the same name by [[Wilson Collison]], directed by [[Frank R. Strayer]], and starring [[Evelyn Brent]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/88300/The-Crusader/overview|title=The Crusader|accessdate=September 25, 2011|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA pushy newspaper reporter Eddie Crane ([[Ned Sparks]]) schemes to get rid of crusading District Attorney Phillip Brandon ([[H. B. Warner]]). Complicating matters is the sordid past of Brandon's wife Tess ([[Evelyn Brent]]) as well as his sister Marcia's affair with a gangster.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Evelyn Brent]] as Tess Brandon\n* [[H. B. Warner]] as Phillip Brandon\n* [[Lew Cody]] as Jimmie Dale\n* [[Ned Sparks]] as Eddie Crane\n* [[Walter Byron (actor)|Walter Byron]] as Joe Carson\n* [[Marceline Day]] as Marcia Brandon\n* [[John St. Polis]] as Robert Henley\n* [[Arthur Hoyt]] as Oscar Shane\n* [[Joseph W. Girard]] as Corrigan\n* [[Syd Saylor]] as Harry Smaltz\n* [[Lloyd Ingraham]] as Alton\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0022794|title=The Crusader}}\n\n{{Frank R. Strayer}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crusader}}\n[[Category:1932 films]]\n[[Category:1932 drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Frank R. Strayer]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Majestic Pictures films]]\n\n{{1930s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1932 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Crusader\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Frank R. Strayer]]\n| producer       = [[Phil Goldstone]] <br> [[Larry Darmour]]\n| writer         = [[Wilson Collison]] (play)<br>[[Edward T. Lowe Jr.]] (sceenplay)\n| starring       = [[Evelyn Brent]]\n| editing        = Otis Garrett\n| distributor    = [[Majestic Pictures]]<br>Capitol Film Exchange (State's Rights)\n| released       = {{film date|1932|10|5}}\n| runtime        = 65 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Crusader''''' is a 1932 American [[Pre-Code Hollywood|pre-Code]]<!--The \"p\" in pre-Code should be lowercased within narrative. See usage in captions and narrative at Pre-Code Hollywood page--> [[drama film]] based upon the play of the same name by [[Wilson Collison]], directed by [[Frank R. Strayer]], and starring [[Evelyn Brent]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/88300/The-Crusader/overview|title=The Crusader|accessdate=September 25, 2011|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nA pushy newspaper reporter Eddie Crane ([[Ned Sparks]]) schemes to get rid of crusading District Attorney Phillip Brandon ([[H. B. Warner]]). Complicating matters is the sordid past of Brandon's wife Tess ([[Evelyn Brent]]) as well as his sister Marcia's affair with a gangster.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Evelyn Brent]] as Tess Brandon\n* [[H. B. Warner]] as Phillip Brandon\n* [[Lew Cody]] as Jimmie Dale\n*